TO PASS THE FIRST PART OF THE RIGHTS OF THE SOUTH RESOLUTION THAT PART BEING: "RESOLVED, THAT THIS GOVERNMENT IS A GOV- ERNMENT OF LIMITED POWERS, AND THAT, BY THE CONSTITUTION OF THE UNITED STATES, CONGRESS HAS NO JURISDICTION WHATEVER OVER THE INSTITUTON OF SLAVERY IN THE SEVERAL STATES OF THE CONFEDERACY."

TO AGREE TO THE SECOND PART OF THE RIGHTS OF THE SOUTH RES- OLUTION, WHICH IS "THAT THE PETITIONS FOR THE ABOLITION OF SLAVERY, AND AGAINST THE REMOVAL OF SLAVES FROM ONE STATE TO ANOTHER, ARE A PART OF A PLAN OF OPERATIONS TO AFFECT THE INSTITUTION OF SAVERY AND TO DESTROY THAT INSTITUTION."
TO PASS THE FIRST SECTION OF THE THIRD PART OF THE RIGHTS OF THE SOUTH RESOLUTION, WHICH IS "THAT CONGRESS HAS NO RIGHT TO DO INDIRECTLY THAT WHICH IT CANNOT DO DIRECTLY."

TO PASS THE SECOND SECTION OF THE THIRD PART OF THE RIGHTS OF THE SOUTH RESOLUTION, WHICH IS "THAT THE AGITATION ON THE SUBJECT OF SLAVERY, WITH THE VIEW OF DESTROYING THAT INSTI- TUTION, IS AGAINST THE TRUE SPIRIT AND MEANING OF THE CON- STITUTION, AND N INFRINGEMENT OF THE RIGHTS OF THE STATES AFFECTED, AND A BREACH OF THE PUBLIC FAITH ON WHICH THEY ENTERED INTO THIS CONFEDERACY."
TO ADOPT THAT PART OF THE RIGHTS OF THE SOUTH RESOLUTION THAT DECLARES THAT "THE CONSTITUTION RESTS ON THE BROAD PRINCIPLE OF EQUALITY AMONG THE MEMBERS OF THIS CONFEDERACY.

TO ADOPT THAT PART OF THE RIGHTS OF THE SOUTH RESOLUTION THAT DECLARES "THAT CONGRESS, IN THE EXERCISE OF ITS ACKNOW- LEDGED POWERS HAS NO RIGHT TO DISCRIMINATE BETWEEN THE INSTITUTIONS OF ONE PORTION OF THE STATES AND ANOTHER, WITH A VIEW OF ABOLISHING HE ONE AND PROMOTING THE OTHER."

TO AGREE TO THAT PART OF THE RIGHTS OF THE SOUTH RESOLUTION WHICH DECLARES THAT "ALL ATTEMPTS ON THE PART OF CONGRESS TO ABOLISH SLAVERY, OR TO PROHIBIT THE REMOVAL OF SLAVES FROM STATE TO STATE, OR TO DISCRIMINATE BETWEEN THE INSTITUTIONS OF ONE PORTIONOF THE CONFEDERACY AND ANOTHER, WITH THE VIEWS AFORESAID, ARE IN VIOLATION OF THE CONSTITUTION, DE- STRUCTIVE OF FUNDAMENTAL PRINCIPLE ON WHICH THE UNION OF THESE STATES RESTS, AND BEYOND THE JURISDICTION OF CONGRESS."

TO TABLE THAT PART OF THE RIGHTS OF THE SOUTH RESOLUTION WHICH DECLARES THAT "EVERY PETITION, MEMORIAL, RESOLUTION, PROPOSITION, OR PAPER TOUCHING ON SLAVERY OR THE ABOLITION THEREOF, SHALL BE TABLED WITHOUT BEING DEBATED, PRINTED OR REFERRED."
TO ADOPT THAT PART OF THE RIGHTS OF THE SOUTH RESOLUTION WHICH WOULD HAVE TABLED, WITHOUT DEBATE OR CONSIDERATION, ANY PETITIONS RELATING TO SLAVERY OR ITS ABOLITION.
